Trump and the Economy
New York—Financial markets have finally woken up to the fact that Trump is the President of the United States.
The world has endured two years of unfiltered tweets and public remarks from the most powerful person in the world, and the obvious question is, what has kept this going for so long?
On one hand, until now, investors have assumed that Trump only talks but does not act.
As long as he implements tax cuts, deregulation, and other policies favorable to the corporate sector and shareholders, they are willing to give him the benefit of the doubt.
Many people believe that eventually, the "adults in the room" will rein in Trump and ensure that government policies stay within bounds.
This assumption was more or less confirmed during Trump's first year in office, a period during which economic growth and corporate profit expectations—thanks to upcoming tax cuts and deregulation—led to strong stock market performance.
In 2017, U.S. stock indices rose by more than 20%.
But in 2018, the situation turned sharply downward, especially in the last few months.
Although corporate profits increased by more than 20% (thanks to tax cuts), the U.S. stock market fluctuated throughout most of the year and is now sharply declining.
Currently, various indices are in correction territory (i.e., down 10% from recent highs), and technology stock indices (such as the Nasdaq) have fallen into a bear market (down 20% or more).
Although the increased volatility in financial markets reflects concerns about China, Italy, and other eurozone economies, as well as key emerging economies, the recent turmoil is due to Trump.
At the beginning of the year, Trump implemented reckless tax cuts, which resulted in rising long-term interest rates, pushing an economy already near full employment to its peak.
By February, concerns that inflation would rise above the Federal Reserve's target of 2% led to the first risk-off wave of 2018.
Then, Trump launched a trade war against China and other important trade partners of the United States.
Concerns about the government's protectionist policies have fluctuated throughout the year, but they are now reaching new highs.
Recent US actions toward China seem to be preparing for a comprehensive trade, economic, and geopolitical cold war.
Another concern is that Trump's other policies may lead to stagflation (weakened growth and increased inflation).
After all, Trump is prepared to restrict foreign direct investment and has implemented broad immigration restrictions, which will hinder the growth of the labor supply in the context of an aging population and increasing skill mismatches.
Moreover, the Trump administration has still not proposed infrastructure plans to stimulate private sector productivity or accelerate the transition to a green economy.
On Twitter and other occasions, Trump continuously criticized businesses' hiring, production, investment, and pricing practices, especially tech companies, which already face widespread opposition and increasingly fierce competition from Chinese rivals.
Emerging markets have also been impacted by U.S. policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening have raised short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the dollar.
As a result, emerging economies have experienced capital flight and an increase in the value of dollar-denominated debt.
Emerging economies heavily reliant on exports have suffered losses due to falling commodity prices, and even countries with only indirect trade ties to China have felt the effects of the trade war.
Even Trump's oil policy has created volatility.
The US reinstatement of sanctions against Iran drove up oil prices, and subsequently, the US government's cancellation of exemptions and intimidation of Saudi Arabia to increase oil production led to a crash in oil prices.
Although American consumers benefited from low oil prices, the stock prices of American energy companies could not hold up.
Moreover, excessive oil price volatility is detrimental to both producers and consumers, as it hinders wise investment and consumption decisions.
Worse still, now it is evident that the benefits from last year's tax cuts have almost entirely flowed to the corporate sector, rather than to households in the form of higher real (inflation-adjusted) wages.
This means that household consumption may soon decelerate, further affecting the economy.
However, the main reason for the recent sharp decline in U.S. and global stock markets was Trump's own words and actions.
Worse than the prominent risk of a full-scale trade war with China (although he recently reached a "ceasefire" with Chinese President Xi Jinping) is Trump's public criticism of the Federal Reserve. His criticism began in spring 2018, when U.S. economic growth was above 4%.
Due to these earlier criticisms, the markets became highly sensitive when the Federal Reserve correctly decided to raise interest rates this month, while hinting that it would raise rates more slowly in 2019.
More likely, the Federal Reserve's relatively hawkish stance is a response to Trump's criticism of it.
Facing hostile tweets from the president, Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell needs to send signals that the central bank still maintains political independence.
But then, after Congress refused to fund his useless Mexico border wall, Trump decided to partially shut down the federal government.
This move put the market into a near-panic state, and soon after the government shutdown, reports emerged that Trump wanted to fire Powell — this could turn market corrections into a crash.
On the eve of the Christmas holiday, U.S. Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin was forced to make a public statement to calm the markets.
He claimed that Trump had no plans to fire Powell and that the U.S. fiscal situation was sound — which precisely highlighted the question of whether the situation was really sound.
And recent internal government personnel changes, which may not directly affect economic decision-making, have also caused market concern.
White House Chief of Staff John Kelly and Defense Secretary James Mattis are about to leave, leaving Trump's cabinet without any sane individuals.
What remains will be all economic nationalists and foreign policy hawks, following Trump's lead blindly.
Currently, the possibility of a comprehensive geopolitical conflict with China cannot be ruled out.
A new cold war is likely to lead to deglobalization and disrupt global supply chains, but the tech industry will be hit hardest, as evidenced by recent cases involving ZTE and Huawei.
At the same time, Trump seems determined to undermine the cohesion of the EU and NATO when the European economy and politics are unstable.
The special counsel Robert Mueller's investigation into Trump's 2016 campaign and its relationship with Russia is the sword of Damocles hanging over Trump's presidency.
Trump is now the Dr. Strangelove of financial markets.
Like the paranoid madman in Stanley Kubrick's classic film, he is deeply trapped in a mutual assured economic destruction.
Now, the market has seen this danger, and the risks of a financial crisis and global recession are rising sharply.
